      "content": "The sudden onset of CAT can be unsettling for pilots and passengers alike. Research suggests that the physical sensation of CAT can be quite distinct from other types of turbulence. Some pilots describe it as a \"sudden jolt\" or a \"brief, intense shake\" that can be felt throughout the aircraft.\n\nIn terms of the physical sensations, pilots often report feeling a brief, intense vibration or shaking, followed by a sudden drop or increase in altitude. This can be accompanied by a feeling of weightlessness or a brief loss of control. The shaking can be intense enough to cause loose objects to fall or to make it difficult to maintain control of the aircraft.\n\nOne theory is that CAT can cause a brief, intense \"flutter\" of the aircraft's wings, which can be felt by the pilots as a sudden, intense vibration. This flutter can be so intense that it can cause the aircraft to shake or rattle, making it difficult to maintain control.\n\nIt's worth noting that pilots are often trained to recognize the physical sensations of CAT, and they may alert air traffic control or other crew members if they suspect that the aircraft is experiencing turbulence. However, even with training, CAT can still be a challenging and unsettling experience for pilots and passengers alike.",
